<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-886-400  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 886 400.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Nov 13 1989 v6 n45 p155(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Chart notes. (facsimile systems glossary) (buyers guide)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT/><TEXT>The chart on Page 156 lists PC facsimile boards that let users sendPC-created text or graphics files directly to a fax machine or another faxboard over telephone lines.andM;The Aug.andP;  28 Buyers' Guide on this topic provides additional information.andO;All information was supplied by the vendors.andM;Conversion approach and sending capabilities: The conversion approachdescribes what must occur so that an ASCII text file can be transmitted as afacsimile.andM;In all cases, the file must be converted into a fax-compatible, bit-mappedimage.andP;  Some fax boards convert the entire file to a fax image first; thisrequires enough disk capacity on the PC to store the entire bit-mapped file.andO;Other facsimile boards convert and send the file as a single operation, nolonger requiring the entire image to be stored.andM;Before converting the text to a fax image, some PC facsimile boards requirethe text files to be converted into pure ASCII.andP;  Others may accept files fromword processors without alteration.andM;Other features: Optical character recognition (OCR) allows the fax board toconvert a received bit-mapped image back into ASCII text.andM;-- Chart compiled by Robin Brazeau</TEXT></DOC>